Photo @amivitale // The tufts of the mane of an orphaned adolescent Gr√©vy's zebra are shown at @r.e.s.c.u.e in northern Kenya. In addition to caring for and raising orphaned baby elephants, @r.e.s.c.u.e is home to orphan giraffes, zebra, kudu, gerenuk, warthogs, and waterbuck. One day, they will all be released back into the wild to live as they were always meant to. Also known as the imperial zebra, the Gr√©vy's zebra is taller, has larger ears, and its stripes are narrower than other types of zebra. It is also an extremely threatened animal. There are only 2,000 Gr√©vy's zebras left in the wild.

