Photo by @amivitale // A brown bear takes a break from feasting on salmon in Kamchatka, Russia. The bear is the largest carnivore in Eurasia. The Kamchatka Peninsula was once entirely populated by brown bears. In remote protected areas it still has some of the highest densities of brown bears on Earth. However, fragmentation, poaching, and dramatic declines in salmon populations due to human fishing are putting increasing pressures on the bears and the communities near them.

Follow @amivitale for more stories about our connections to the natural world.

@thephotosociety #bears #kamchatka #russia #conservation #brownbears

Photo by @amivitale // Black rhinos Balozi, left, and Morris greet each other at @OlPejeta Conservancy in Kenya. An estimated 5,630 black rhinos remain in the wild. Over 500,000 rhinos once roamed Asia, Africa, and Europe; today the total number of all five rhino species worldwide is only 27,300. They need our support. @OlPejeta is the largest black rhino sanctuary in northern Kenya, and also home to 30 southern white rhinos and the last two northern white rhinos on the planet.

Please follow @amivitale and @olpejeta to learn more, including how you can help.

